\begin_layout Enumerate
Writing out the derivation in 18.02 fashion, this is tedious but straightforward:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
\nabla\cdot(\vec{u}\times\vec{v}) & =\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
\frac{\partial}{\partial x} & \frac{\partial}{\partial y} & \frac{\partial}{\partial z}\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
u_{y}v_{z}-u_{z}v_{y}\\
u_{z}v_{x}-u_{x}v_{z}\\
u_{x}v_{y}-u_{y}v_{x}
\end{array}\right)\\
 & =\frac{\partial(u_{y}v_{z}-u_{z}v_{y})}{\partial x}+\frac{\partial(u_{z}v_{x}-u_{x}v_{z})}{\partial y}+\frac{\partial(u_{x}v_{y}-u_{y}v_{x})}{\partial z}\\
 & =\left(\frac{\partial u_{z}}{\partial y}-\frac{\partial u_{y}}{\partial z}\right)v_{x}+\left(\frac{\partial u_{x}}{\partial z}-\frac{\partial u_{z}}{\partial x}\right)v_{y}+\left(\frac{\partial u_{y}}{\partial x}-\frac{\partial u_{x}}{\partial y}\right)v_{z}\\
 & \qquad u_{x}\left(\frac{\partial v_{y}}{\partial z}-\frac{\partial v_{z}}{\partial y}\right)+u_{y}\left(\frac{\partial v_{z}}{\partial x}-\frac{\partial v_{x}}{\partial z}\right)+u_{z}\left(\frac{\partial v_{x}}{\partial y}-\frac{\partial v_{y}}{\partial x}\right)\\
 & =(\nabla\times\vec{u})\cdot\vec{v}-\vec{u}\cdot(\nabla\times\vec{v}).
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

(A much more compact derivation is possible using Einstein notation and
 the Levi--Civit√° tensor, but probably most of you haven't seen this notation.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Given the above identity, integration by parts is straightforwards: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
\langle\vec{u},\nabla\times\vec{v}\rangle & =\int_{\Omega}\bar{\vec{u}}\cdot(\nabla\times\vec{v})=\int_{\Omega}\left[\nabla\cdot(\bar{\vec{u}}\times\vec{v})+\overline{\nabla\times\vec{u}}\cdot\vec{v}\right]\\
 & =\oiint_{\partial\Omega}(\bar{\vec{u}}\times\vec{v})\cdot d\vec{S}+\langle\nabla\times\vec{u},\vec{v}\rangle,
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

applying the divergence theorem in the second line.
 So, the surface term 
\begin_inset Formula $\oiint_{\partial\Omega}\vec{w}\cdot d\vec{S}$
\end_inset

 is for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{\vec{w}=\bar{\vec{u}}\times\vec{v}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We must have 
\begin_inset Formula $(\bar{\vec{u}}\times\vec{v})\cdot d\vec{S}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $d\vec{S}=\vec{n}\, dS$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{n}$
\end_inset

 is the outward unit normal vector at each point on 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 Then we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\vec{u}}\times\vec{v}\perp\vec{n}$
\end_inset

, which is true if, for example, both 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 are parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{n}$
\end_inset

 at the boundary.
 i.e.
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{\left.\vec{u}\times\vec{n}\right|_{\partial\Omega}=0}$
\end_inset

.
 It is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 necessary to require 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\vec{u}\right|_{\partial\Omega}=0$
\end_inset

 on the boundary, and that answer will not be accepted as I specifically
 requested that you not constrain all the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 on the boundary.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Another way to see this is to write 
\begin_inset Formula $(\bar{\vec{u}}\times\vec{v})\cdot d\vec{S}=\vec{n}\cdot(\bar{\vec{u}}\times\vec{v})dS=\vec{v}\cdot(\vec{n}\times\bar{\vec{u}})dS=\bar{\vec{u}}\cdot(\vec{v}\times\vec{n})dS$
\end_inset

 by elementary triple-product identities, and hence we again see that it
 is sufficient to have 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}\times\vec{n}=0$
\end_inset

 on the boundary.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Although I will accept the above answer, it is actually possible to contrive
 a slightly weaker condition: 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 can have components 
\begin_inset Formula $\perp$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{n}$
\end_inset

 on the boundary, as long as those surface-parallel components are 
\emph on
in the same direction
\emph default
 for both 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 (to obtain zero cross product).
 That is, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 is some surface-parallel (
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}\perp\vec{n})$
\end_inset

 vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\Omega$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
By the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hairy ball theorem
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of topology, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}$
\end_inset

 must vanish somewhere on 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\Omega$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is simply connected (no holes), at which point 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 must be parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Then it is sufficient for the surface-parallel component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\perp$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}$
\end_inset

 everywhere on the boundary, or equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\vec{u}\cdot\vec{p}\right|_{\partial\Omega}=0$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

[Actually, there are other possible conditions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 if we allow non-local boundary conditions, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 at one point on the boundary is related to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 at another point.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is a cube and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
periodic
\emph default
 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 on one face equals 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 on the opposite face), then the 
\begin_inset Formula $\oiint_{\partial\Omega}$
\end_inset

 vanishes because each face of the cube cancels the opposite face, without
 requiring any component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 to be zero.]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We just 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

integrate by parts
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 twice: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
\langle\vec{u},\nabla\times\nabla\times\vec{v}\rangle & =\int_{\Omega}\bar{\vec{u}}\cdot(\nabla\times\nabla\times\vec{v})=\cancel{\oiint_{\partial\Omega}[\bar{\vec{u}}\times(\nabla\times\vec{v})]\cdot d\vec{S}}+\int_{\Omega}(\nabla\times\bar{\vec{u}})\cdot(\nabla\times\vec{v})\\
 & =\cancel{\oiint_{\partial\Omega}[(\nabla\times\bar{\vec{u}})\times\vec{v}]\cdot d\vec{S}}+\int_{\Omega}(\nabla\times\nabla\times\bar{\vec{u}})\cdot\vec{v}=\langle\nabla\times\nabla\times\vec{u},\vec{v}\rangle,
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

where the surface terms cancel if 
\emph on
either
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{\left.\vec{u}\times\vec{n}\right|_{\partial\Omega}=0}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{\left.(\nabla\times\vec{u})\times\vec{n}\right|_{\partial\Omega}=0}$
\end_inset

, that is if either 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 or its curl are normal to the surface.
 (As in the previous part, one can actually weaken this slightly, but this
 is sufficient for our purposes.)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

To check definiteness, carry integration by parts 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

halfway
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 through: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle\vec{u},\nabla\times\nabla\times\vec{u}\rangle=\int_{\Omega}|\nabla\times\vec{u}|^{2}\geq0,
\]

\end_inset

so it is 
\series bold
positive semidefinite
\series default
.
 It is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 positive-definite since 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times\vec{u}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}=\nabla\phi\neq0$
\end_inset

 for 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 non-constant scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 , and we can easily choose such a 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\phi$
\end_inset

 satisfies the boundary conditions (e.g., choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 so that it is constant in a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\Omega$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Taking the curl of both sides of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times\vec{E}=-\frac{\partial\vec{B}}{\partial t},$
\end_inset

 we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times\nabla\times\vec{E}=-\nabla\times\frac{\partial\vec{B}}{\partial t}=-\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\nabla\times\vec{B}=-\frac{\partial^{2}\vec{E}}{\partial t^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial^{2}\vec{E}}{\partial t^{2}}=\hat{A}\vec{E}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}=-\nabla\times\nabla\times$
\end_inset

.
 From the previous parts, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}\perp\vec{n}$
\end_inset

 at the surface, this 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 is self-adjoint and negative semidefinite, and hence we have a 
\series bold
hyperbolic equation
\series default
.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

As in class, we therefore expect orthogonal eigenfunctions and real 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\leq0$
\end_inset

, and hence oscillating 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

normal mode
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 solutions with eigenfrequencies 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\sqrt{-\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

[Technically, we also obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

 solutions which are non-oscillatory---from above, these are nullspace solutions
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}=\nabla\phi$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, which physically correspond to the time-independent fields of fix charge
 distributions, where 
\begin_inset Formula $-\phi$
\end_inset

 is the potential and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\cdot\vec{E}=\nabla^{2}\phi$
\end_inset

 is the charge density.
 Everything else, all of the other eigenfunctions, are oscillating solutions.]
